is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CsA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9894912242889404, "span": {"begin": 997, "end": 1000}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9798064231872559, "span": {"begin": 1086, "end": 1090}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3725"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AP-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9962105751037598, "span": {"begin": 1091, "end": 1095}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:111188159"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "IL-2 promoters", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9946079850196838, "span": {"begin": 1142, "end": 1156}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.8747904300689697, "span": {"begin": 1180, "end": 1184}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3725"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AP-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9974858164787292, "span": {"begin": 1185, "end": 1189}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:37153"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CNI", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.502876341342926, "span": {"begin": 1245, "end": 1248}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9794889688491821, "span": {"begin": 1299, "end": 1303}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3725", "2353", "3726", "3727", "2354"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AP-1 complex", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9030964970588684, "span": {"begin": 1304, "end": 1316}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9942507743835449, "span": {"begin": 1375, "end": 1379}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3725"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AP-1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9976392984390259, "span": {"begin": 1380, "end": 1384}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016559"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FK506", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9973322153091431, "span": {"begin": 1438, "end": 1443}}, {"id": ["mesh:D016559"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "FK506", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9984468817710876, "span": {"begin": 1487, "end": 1492}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4773"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NFAT", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.982211172580719, "span": {"begin": 1540, "end": 1544}}], "text": "The relationship&nbsp;of nuclear localization of NFAT leading to reduced NFAT/AP-1 complex formation bound at the promoter sites of cytokine genes in the presence of CNIs is well known as mentioned above.  Imaging flowcytometry revealed that concentration-dependent reduction of in vitro nuclear localization of NFAT was evident at the maximum concentration of 1&nbsp;&micro;M with minimal concentration of 0.1nM (Jurkat human T cell line) or 10nM (CD4+T cells from whole blood) after 2 hours treatment of tacrolimus (Maguire et al. 2013).  Gel mobility shift assays using Ar-5 human T cells stimulated with cross-linked anti-CD3 antibody showed that NFAT/AP-1 (cFos and Jun) complexes were found only in the nuclear extract with preexisting NFAT in the cytoplasm after T cell stimulation and that the NFAT/AP-1 complexes in the nucleus decreased after 2 hours treatment with CsA at 1&micro;M (Jain et al. 1992). Decreased NFAT translocated to the nucleus, induced by FK506 at 100ng/mL (124nM) or CsA at 500ng/mL (416nM) after 2 hours treatment, hinders the formation of the functional NFAT/AP-1 complexes necessary to binding at the site of IL-2 promoters (Flanagan et al. 1991) NFAT/AP-1 complex formation was also reported to be inhibited by CNI (Rao et al. 1997).  Quantitative understanding of NFAT/AP-1 complex formation in the nucleus is insufficient although nuclear NFAT/AP-1 complex formation was shown to be inhibited&nbsp; by FK506 at concentrations within the&nbsp;range of FK506 for the inhibition of nuclear translocation of NFAT.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:54:21 +0000 2026"}